83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
House Bill 4088
Sponsored by Representative FRAGALA, Senators REYNOLDS, PROZANSKI, Representatives CHAICHI,
CHOTZEN, DOBSON, RIEKE SMITH, VALDERRAMA, Senators GELSER BLOUIN, MANNING JR,
PATTERSON, PHAM K; Representatives GOMBERG, GRAYBER, HUDSON, MCDONALD, MCLAIN, MUNOZ,
NOSSE, PHAM H, WALTERS, WISE, Senators CAMPOS, FREDERICK, JAMA, NERON MISSLIN (Presession
filed.)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure as introduced. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability
standards.
Digest: The Act says that it is the policy of this state to make sure people are allowed to get
certain kinds of health care, including care for their bodies and gender identity. The Act also makes
changes to laws about helping the federal government and other states in cases arising involving
this kind of care, makes some records and information private and says that midwives who give this
kind of care will not get in trouble if they follow the rules. The new law starts right away. (Flesch
Readability Score: 60.7).
Declares this state’s policy to protect engagement in certain activities relating to reproductive
health care and gender-affirming treatment.
Prohibits cooperation with law enforcement agencies of the federal government or other states
in actions involving legally-protected reproductive or gender-affirming health care activities.
Modifies provisions regarding interstate actions involving legally-protected reproductive or
gender-affirming health care activities.
Makes specified records and information confidential.
Provides protection from disciplinary action for direct entry midwives who provide reproductive
health care and gender-affirming treatment under specified circumstances.
Declares an emergency, effective on passage.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to health; creating new provisions; amending ORS 15.430, 24.500, 33.420, 33.460, 192.345,
3 435.190, 676.612 and 687.445; and declaring an emergency.
4 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
5
6 INTERSTATE ACTIONS
7
8 SECTION 1. Policy regarding legal protections for reproductive or gender-affirming
9 health care activities. (1) “Gender-affirming treatment” and “reproductive health care” have
10 the meanings given those terms in ORS 24.500.
11 (2) It is the policy of this state that people should be protected under state law to engage
12 in the following activities related to reproductive health care or gender-affirming treatment
13 that is provided by a health care provider who is licensed in this state, who is acting within
14 the health care provider’s scope of practice and who provides or attempts to provide the
15 reproductive health care or gender-affirming treatment to a patient who is physically located
16 in this state:
17 (a) The receipt or attempted receipt of reproductive health care or gender-affirming
18 treatment that is lawful in this state.
19 (b) The provision or attempted provision of reproductive health care or gender-affirming
20 treatment that is lawful in this state.
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 49

HB 4088
1 (c) The assistance or attempted assistance in the receipt or provision of reproductive
2 health care or gender-affirming treatment that is lawful in this state.
3 SECTION 2. Nonfugitive extradition. (1) As used in this section, “legally-protected re-
4 productive or gender-affirming health care activities” means one or more of the activities
5 described in section 1 of this 2026 Act.
6 (2) Except as required by federal law and notwithstanding ORS 133.767, the Governor of
7 this state may not surrender, on demand of the executive authority of any other state, a
8 person in this state charged in such other state for engaging in legally-protected reproduc-
9 tive or gender-affirming health care activities if the Governor is not otherwise required to
10 surrender the person under ORS 133.747.
11 SECTION 3. Cooperation with federal and interstate investigations. (1) As used in this
12 section:
13 (a) “Legally-protected reproductive or gender-affirming health care activities” means one
14 or more of the activities described in section 1 of this 2026 Act.
15 (b) “Public body” means a public body as defined in ORS 174.109 and the Oregon Health
16 and Science University.
17 (2) Except as provided in ORS 24.500 and 133.747, or as required by federal law, an officer,
18 employee or agent of a public body may not cooperate with, provide information to or oth-
19 erwise expend or use time, moneys, facilities, property, equipment, personnel or other re-
20 sources to assist a federal law enforcement agency, a law enforcement agency of another
21 state, a private citizen or a quasi-law enforcement agent in relation to an investigation or
22 inquiry into a legally-protected reproductive or gender-affirming health care activity, if such
23 activity would be lawful if it occurred entirely in this state.
