11 SECTION 5. ORS 24.500 is amended to read:
12 24.500. (1) As used in this section:
13 (a) “Gender-affirming treatment” means a procedure, service, drug, device or product that a
14 physical or behavioral health care provider prescribes to treat an individual for incongruence be-
15 tween the individual’s gender identity and the individual’s sex assignment at birth.
16 (b) “Reproductive health” means reproductive processes, functions and systems at all stages of
17 life.
18 (c) “Reproductive health care” includes family planning and contraception, pregnancy termi-
19 nation services, prenatal, postnatal and delivery care, miscarriage management, fertility care,
20 sterilization services, treatments for sexually transmitted infections and reproductive cancers and
21 any other health care and medical services related to reproductive health.
22 (2) A law of another state that authorizes a person to bring a civil or criminal action against
23 [a person that] another person who does any of the following is contrary to the public policy of this
24 state:
25 (a) [Receive] Receives or attempts to receive reproductive health care or gender-affirming
26 treatment;
27 (b) [Provide or attempt] Provides or attempts to provide reproductive health care or gender-
28 affirming treatment; or
29 (c) Knowingly [engage in conduct that aids or abets] engages in conduct that aids or encour-
30 ages or attempts to aid or encourage the provision of reproductive health care or gender-
31 affirming treatment.
32 (3) Notwithstanding ORCP 38 C, a person may not request that a clerk of court issue a subpoena
33 for service upon a person to whom a foreign subpoena is directed if the foreign subpoena relates to
34 gender-affirming treatment or reproductive health care services that are permitted under the laws
35 of this state, unless the person requesting the subpoena provides a written declaration that the
36 foreign subpoena relates to:
37 (a) An out-of-state action founded in tort, contract or statute, for which a similar claim would
38 exist under the laws of this state, brought by a patient or the patient’s authorized legal represen-
39 tative, for damages suffered by the patient; or
40 (b) An out-of-state action founded in contract, and for which a similar claim would exist under
41 the laws of this state, brought or sought to be enforced by a party with a contractual relationship
42 with the person that is the subject of the subpoena.
